    <section id="genetics-polygenic-risk" class="reveal">
      <h2>Genetics, Polygenic Risk Scores, and the Personalized Thyroid</h2>

      <p>The large-scale genome-wide association studies now characterizing the genetic architecture of thyroid disease represent a shift from treating thyroid conditions as dichotomous (present or absent) to treating them as polygenic traits distributed across a population.</p>

      <p>A 2025 analysis reported in <em>Nature Reviews Endocrinology</em> identified hundreds of genetic loci associated with hypothyroidism and thyroid hormone levels. The magnitude of this finding is significant: it means that the predisposition to thyroid dysfunction is distributed across many genetic variants, each with small individual effect, but collectively accounting for a substantial portion of population variation in thyroid hormone levels and autoimmune thyroid disease susceptibility.</p>

      <p>Polygenic risk scores (PRS) — aggregate measures of an individual's genetic burden across all relevant loci — can predict who will develop thyroid disease years before clinical symptoms appear. This has immediate implications for screening and preventive strategy: high-PRS individuals could be targeted for earlier and more intensive thyroid monitoring, for proactive iodine status optimization, and for more aggressive management of modifiable environmental exposures.</p>

      <p>For treatment, the DIO2 genetics story from Part 1 is the leading edge of what personalized thyroid medicine will look like. The Thr92Ala DIO2 polymorphism is already identified in academic endocrinology settings as a clinical consideration for patients failing to respond adequately to levothyroxine monotherapy. As genetic testing costs continue to fall and as the clinical evidence base for DIO2-guided treatment decisions continues to accumulate, genotyping at the DIO2 locus — and potentially the MCT10 transporter locus — will likely become standard before initiating thyroid hormone replacement therapy in patients where combination T4/T3 therapy might be appropriate.</p>

      <p>The population-level implication is equally significant. If DIO2 Thr92Ala homozygotes — roughly 12–15% of the European-ancestry population — show increased Alzheimer's disease risk attributable to chronic localized brain hypothyroidism despite normal serum TSH, then identifying these individuals early and ensuring their cerebral T3 supply is adequate represents a potentially important avenue for neurodegeneration prevention. This is speculative at this stage — the causal evidence for the Alzheimer's association is not yet established — but the mechanistic pathway (ER stress in glial cells, localized hypothyroidism, gene expression profiles consistent with neurodegeneration) is coherent enough to be formally investigated.</p>
    </section>

