    <section id="t3-question-resolved" class="reveal">
      <h2>The T3 Question, Resolved</h2>

      <p>The liothyronine debate has raged in endocrinology for three decades, largely because the relevant clinical trials were not designed to detect what they were looking for — benefit in genetically stratified subgroups — and instead measured average effects across genetically heterogeneous populations.</p>

      <p>The emerging clinical framework for T3 supplementation — informed by the 2024 UK Biobank analysis, the WATTS study genetics, the DIO2 mechanistic research, and the JCI mouse model data — looks approximately like this:</p>

      <p>For patients with levothyroxine-treated hypothyroidism who report persistent symptoms (fatigue, cognitive fog, mood disturbance) despite TSH normalization, the clinical evaluation should include: measurement of free T3 and reverse T3 (to identify functional T3 deficiency in the peripheral compartment); DIO2 and MCT10 genotyping; assessment of selenium, iron, and iodine status; and evaluation of gut health and chronic inflammatory status. This is not yet standard practice. It represents the practice ceiling that the evidence currently supports.</p>

      <p>For patients with the DIO2 Ala/Ala genotype, or the combined DIO2/MCT10 variant pattern, combination T4/T3 therapy — or desiccated thyroid extract — is now backed by mechanistic rationale, genetic association data, and clinical observation in a way that justifies a formal treatment trial in individual patients, carefully monitored with regular T3 and TSH assessment to avoid over-replacement.</p>

      <p>The European Thyroid Association guidelines currently classify T4/T3 combination therapy as an "experimental" option to be considered only in patients whose symptoms persist despite TSH normalization. This classification — "experimental" — will likely migrate toward "conditionally recommended for genetically stratified patients" as the genetic evidence accumulates further and as the clinical trials designed to test this question (with genetic stratification as a primary variable) are completed.</p>

      <p>Peat's clinical intuition — that the standard levothyroxine monotherapy fails a significant subset of patients, that T3 availability is the operative variable, and that measuring TSH alone is insufficient — has been retrospectively vindicated by the molecular biology of DIO2. The intuition preceded the mechanism. The mechanism is now established. The practice change is lagging.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="sleep-thyroid-aging" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Sleep-Thyroid-Aging Triangle</h2>

      <p>Part 2 noted the emerging research on sleep and thyroid function. For a complete picture of what future thyroid management will integrate, this intersection deserves its own examination.</p>

      <p>TSH secretion is profoundly circadian, with the secretory peak occurring between midnight and 4 AM. This nocturnal TSH surge is the primary driver of the 20–40% higher TSH values seen in early morning blood draws compared to afternoon draws — a source of diagnostic inconsistency that is rarely addressed by standardizing draw timing. More fundamentally, the circadian regulation of TSH secretion means that chronic circadian disruption — from shift work, artificial light exposure at night, and social jetlag — continuously blunts the physiological TSH peak and, over time, alters the pituitary-thyroid feedback dynamics.</p>

      <p>In aging, TSH levels rise while T3 levels fall slightly. This pattern — higher TSH, lower T3 — has been hypothesized to represent either a protective adaptation (conserving metabolic rate in aging tissues that would otherwise be metabolically overdriven) or a pathological loss of regulatory precision in the hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid axis. The answer matters enormously for whether age-related "subclinical hypothyroidism" in the elderly should be treated.</p>

      <p>A compelling longitudinal analysis from the Whickham cohort, published in December 2024, found that TSH increased from a mean of 1.94 to 2.18 mIU/L over 7.8 years of follow-up in older individuals, while free T4 remained stable and free T3 decreased slightly. Thyroid antibodies decreased over the same period. When age-appropriate reference ranges were applied, the rate of subclinical hypothyroidism diagnosis fell from 9.0% to 2% using standard versus age-specific ranges. The implication is not just diagnostic recalibration — it is that the TSH rise in the elderly may represent normal physiology, and treating it pharmacologically may produce harm (cardiac arrhythmia, bone loss, anxiety) by suppressing a compensatory adaptation.</p>

      <p>Interestingly, research on Italian centenarians found that older people from longevity-associated families had lower T4 and T3 levels and higher TSH levels — and so did the children and nieces and nephews of these centenarians. This suggests the thyroid phenotype associated with longevity may actually include modestly elevated TSH, not the lower TSH values associated with peak metabolic rate in younger adults. The bioenergetic logic — that lower metabolic rate in aging may reduce oxidative stress and slow certain degenerative processes — is not without theoretical basis, even if it conflicts with Peat's emphasis on maintaining high thyroid function throughout life. The truth here is probably age-dependent: optimizing T3 availability in working-age adults may have different risk-benefit calculus than aggressively treating TSH elevations in octogenarians.</p>
    </section>

