    <section id="thyroid-of-2035" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Thyroid of 2035: A Speculative but Evidence-Based Picture</h2>

      <p>Integrating the trajectories established across the preceding five parts, the thyroid medicine of a decade from now will likely look like this:</p>

      <p><strong>Screening</strong> will be more comprehensive and more targeted simultaneously. Universal first-trimester thyroid screening for pregnant women — TSH, free T4, TPO antibodies — will be standard, driven by the accumulating evidence linking maternal thyroid status to autism risk, miscarriage, and cognitive outcomes in offspring. For the general population, polygenic risk scoring will identify high-burden individuals for earlier and more intensive monitoring. Age-specific reference ranges will be standard, reducing overdiagnosis in the elderly.</p>

      <p><strong>Diagnosis</strong> will be multimodal. The TSH + free T4 panel will be augmented with free T3, reverse T3, and antibody testing as the standard thyroid workup, not as an extended panel requiring specialist justification. DIO2 genotyping will be routinely incorporated into the workup for symptomatic patients who are candidates for thyroid hormone replacement. AI-assisted ultrasound will be standard of care for nodule assessment, reducing biopsy rates and improving malignancy detection accuracy.</p>

      <p><strong>Treatment</strong> will be personalized. The DIO2 genotype will inform the choice between levothyroxine monotherapy, combination T4/T3 therapy, and desiccated thyroid extract. Selenium status will be assessed and corrected as standard practice before and during Hashimoto's management. Microbiome-targeted adjuncts — specific probiotics, FMT for refractory cases, dietary modifications — will be integrated into autoimmune thyroid disease management as the clinical trial data mature.</p>

      <p><strong>Environmental medicine</strong> will be part of thyroid care. The clinical history for thyroid patients will include PFAS exposure assessment (military service, firefighting, contaminated water districts), dietary iodine intake, BPA and phthalate exposure reduction counseling, and sleep quality evaluation. These are not alternative medicine additions. They are physiologically justified interventions for a disease whose upstream drivers are increasingly understood.</p>

      <p><strong>Cancer management</strong> will be governed by molecular risk rather than histological staging. Surveillance for low-risk microcarcinomas will be the default, not surgery. Thermal ablation will be broadly available. Genetic profiling at diagnosis will guide adjuvant therapy decisions. Targeted therapies for advanced disease will extend survival further.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="closing" class="reveal">
      <h2>Closing: What the Thyroid Deserves</h2>

      <p>The thyroid gland weighs less than an ounce. It sits in a location most people could not identify on their own body. It produces two hormones that are, directly or through conversion, responsible for the metabolic rate of every cell in the body, the architecture of the fetal brain, the integrity of the cardiovascular system, the function of the gut, and — via T3's role in mitochondrial energy production — the basic biological vitality that determines how alert, warm, energetic, and cognitively capable you feel on any given day.</p>

      <p>It is disrupted, at sub-clinical levels, by industrial chemicals now present in the blood and tissue of virtually every person alive. It is attacked, in tens of millions of people, by autoimmune processes whose upstream origins in the gut are only now being systematically investigated. It is tested with a single indirect proxy that cannot see what is happening inside cells. It is treated, when treatment is given at all, with a single hormone that a significant genetic minority cannot adequately convert to the active form their tissues need.</p>

      <p>The field of thyroidology is not in crisis. It is, in the most honest sense, catching up. The tools to do better exist. The evidence base to act on them is accumulating, faster now than at any prior point in the history of this discipline. What remains is the will — of institutions, of reimbursement systems, of practitioners, and of patients who understand enough to demand a more complete account of what their thyroid actually needs.</p>

      <p>This series has tried to provide the foundation for that demand.</p>
    </section>

